modules.description: This module defines and manipulates icon configurations for map markers, supporting both image-based and HTML-based icons. It provides functions to create icon instances with customizable properties such as size, anchor points, and URLs for retina or shadow images, and allows setting a default image path for fallback use. Concrete use cases include customizing marker appearance in a map application, such as defining icon offsets for precise placement or using HTML content for interactive icons.

This module defines a data type `t` to represent geographic coordinates with latitude and longitude values. It provides functions to create, access, and compare coordinate points, ensuring accurate positional checks within a small margin of error. It supports conversion to and from JavaScript values for interoperability in web applications.

This module defines operations for creating and managing different types of map layers such as tile layers, GeoJSON layers, markers, and vector layers. It provides functions to add or remove layers from a map, bind and control popups, and handle events specific to each layer type. Concrete use cases include displaying geographic data with `create_geojson`, adding interactive markers with popup support, and rendering polylines or circle markers on a map.

This module implements interactive map markers with customizable appearance and behavior. It supports operations to create markers at specific coordinates, adjust their visual properties like icon, opacity, and z-index, and dynamically update their position. The module works with geographic coordinates, icons, and rendering options to enable use cases like real-time location tracking, custom point-of-interest visualization, and interactive map overlays.

This module creates and manages interactive maps within HTML elements, providing functions to initialize maps on specific containers, adjust their view, and handle user interactions. It supports operations like setting geographical views, fitting maps to world bounds, and managing popups, while working with data types such as latitude-longitude coordinates, zoom levels, and DOM elements. Concrete use cases include embedding dynamic maps in web pages, updating map display in response to user actions, and integrating event handlers for map interactions.

This module defines a point structure with integer `x` and `y` coordinates. It provides conversions to and from JavaScript values using `of_jv` and `to_jv`. Use this module when working with coordinate data that needs to interoperate with JavaScript, such as handling mouse events or positioning elements on a map.

This module defines operations for creating and configuring popups on a map, including setting their position, content, and display options like size constraints, auto-pan behavior, and close controls. It works with geographic coordinates, HTML elements, and a set of popup-specific options that control appearance and interaction. Concrete use cases include displaying dynamic text or HTML content at specific map locations, such as showing detailed information about a map marker or handling user interactions within a popup.

This module handles event types and operations for interacting with Leaflet.js events in OCaml, supporting event constructors like `Click`, `Move_end`, and `Zoom_end`, and providing accessors to event properties such as coordinates, error codes, and event sources. It works with discriminated unions `t` and `sub` to represent event instances and event subscriptions, along with types like `Leaflet.Point.t` and `Leaflet.Latlng.t` for geospatial data. Concrete use cases include handling map click events, retrieving mouse coordinates, and processing error events with specific error codes and messages.

This module provides core components for building interactive maps in OCaml, handling geospatial data, visual elements, and user interactions. It includes modules for managing map layers, markers, popups, and events, with support for coordinate types like `Latlng.t` and `Point.t, and visual configurations such as `Icon.t`. Concrete use cases include rendering GeoJSON data, handling map click events, customizing marker icons, and displaying interactive popups with dynamic content.
